Here's the proper approach using MAUI's lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "NoteDraft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated += OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated += OnAppResumed;
    }

    private void OnAppBackgrounded(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnAppResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Restore draft when app returns
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(NoteEditor.Text))
        {
            NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
        }
    }

    // Clean up to avoid leaks
    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated -= OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated -= OnAppResumed;
    }

    // Clear draft after an intentional save
    private void OnSaveClicked(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // ... your save logic ...
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to the background — save here.
- **`Window.Activated`** fires when the app returns — restore here.
- **`Preferences`** is a simple key-value store that persists across sessions (good for small text). For large content, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead.
- **Unsubscribe** in `OnDisappearing` to prevent memory leaks.
- **Clear the draft** after the user intentionally saves, so stale drafts don't linger.
